        "method": {
            "description": "The present study investigated how experimentally induced reputation concern modulates judgments in moral dilemmas. In a mixed-design experiment, participants were randomly assigned to the observed vs. the control group and responded to a series of trolley-type moral dilemmas either in the presence or absence of observers, respectively.",
            "steps": "1. Recruit participants and screen them for any prior exposure to the moral dilemma literature and for the history of taking advanced psychology courses. Obtain written consent and gree on compensation (for the current study, they received 7000 KRW (=6.50 USD) at the end of the experiment).\n2. To measure individual participant's baseline moral decision tendencies unaffected by experimental manipulation of reputation concern apply a pretest with 20 moral dilemmas (frame it as a practice prior to the main task). For this purpose, the authors adopted a stimuli set from previous studies that applied the process dissociation analysis (PD) to estimate the deontological (D) and utilitarian inclination (U) within individuals.The details are to be found in supplementary material S2-1 and S2-2. In each trial, a brief onset of fixation point is followed by three consecutive segments of a moral dilemma presented through a computer screen. All twenty PD-dilemma scenarios are shown to participants in a randomized order. Participants are to make binary decisions on the appropriateness of the behaviors described at the end of the scenarios (Inappropriate = Deontological judgment; Appropriate = Utilitarian judgment). Once responses were made, participants are further prompted to indicate the level of confidence for each decision on a 4-point Likert scale using a number pad (extreme values correspond to the strong confidence for either deontological (i.e., 1: Very inappropriate) and utilitarian judgment (i.e., 4: Very appropriate), while the moderate values (i.e., 2 and 3) are to depict diminished decision certainty. Every response is followed by a visual feedback (i.e., a red box) highlighting the choice made by participants. To dissociate people's responses with the motor execution, the assigned response keys for binary decisions and the numbering of the Likert scale are to be counterbalanced across individuals.\n3. Proceed to the main task where participants respond to a series of 50 moral dilemmas: 20 personal-moral dilemmas, 15 impersonal-moral dilemmas and 15 non-moral control dilemmas (See Supplementary material S1-1). The distinction between personal- vs.impersonal moral dilemmas was made based on the presence of direct, serious bodily harm towards a person(s). The non-moral dilemmas included mathematical calculation and logical reasoning. A general process was identical to that of the pretest with one additional critical feature: a manipulation of reputation concern through social observation. Before proceeding to the main task, all participants were randomly assigned to either the observed (OBS - where participants were told that their performances will be monitored by two experimenters due to some technical glitch that may cause data loss, and brought to a separate cubicle wherein two experimenters were sitting with a monitoring device connected to the participants' own screen) or the control group (CON - the participants were told that their responses will remain anonymous after the experiment and they encountered the same observers during the instruction phase, but the monitoring device was removed and no observation explanation was given). \n4. Compute the proportion of deontological responses for each participant within each dilemma type (personal, impersonal, non-moral), then analyze these proportions using a 2 × 3 mixed ANOVA with group (OBS vs CON) as the between-subject factor and dilemma type as the within-subject factor.",
